WEBVTT

00:26.480 --> 00:29.280
Part 1

00:30.080 --> 00:32.060
Story of the Door

00:33.200 --> 00:38.660
Mr. Utterson, the lawyer, was a man of a rugged countenance that was never lighted

00:38.660 --> 00:45.280
by a smile, cold, scanty, and embarrassed in discourse, backward in sentiment, lean,

00:45.600 --> 00:50.100
long, dusty, dreary, and yet somehow lovable.

00:50.800 --> 00:57.360
At friendly meetings, and when the wine was to his taste, something eminently human beaconed

00:57.360 --> 01:02.980
from his eye, something indeed which never found its way into his talk, but which spoke

01:02.980 --> 01:09.900
not only in these silent symbols of the after-dinner face, but more often and loudly in the acts

01:09.900 --> 01:10.920
of his life.

01:11.500 --> 01:17.160
He was austere with himself, drank gin when he was alone to mortify a taste for vintages,

01:17.520 --> 01:22.680
and though he enjoyed the theatre, had not crossed the doors of one for twenty years.

01:23.280 --> 01:31.240
But he had an approved tolerance for others, sometimes wondering, almost with envy, at

01:31.240 --> 01:37.700
the high pressure of spirits involved in their misdeeds, and in any extremity inclined to

01:37.700 --> 01:39.880
help rather than to reprove.

01:40.520 --> 01:47.420
I inclined to Cain's heresy, he used to say, quietly, I let my brother go to the devil

01:47.420 --> 01:48.520
in his own way.

01:48.940 --> 01:55.200
In this character it was frequently his fortune to be the last reputable acquaintance and

01:55.200 --> 02:02.380
the last good influence in the lives of down-going men, and to such as these, so long as they

02:02.380 --> 02:07.720
came about his chambers, he never marked a shade of change in his demeanour.

02:08.580 --> 02:15.240
No doubt the feat was easy to Mr. Utterson, for he was undemonstrative at the best, and

02:15.240 --> 02:19.600
Even his friendship seemed to be founded in a similar catholicity of good nature.

02:20.620 --> 02:26.260
It is the mark of a modest man to accept his friendly circle ready-made from the hands

02:26.260 --> 02:29.920
of opportunity, and that was the lawyer's way.

02:30.620 --> 02:35.420
His friends were those of his own blood, or those whom he had known the longest.

02:36.040 --> 02:43.400
His affections, like ivy, were the growth of time, they implied no aptness in the object.

02:44.280 --> 02:50.640
Hence, no doubt, the bond that united him to Mr. Richard Enfield, his distant kinsman,

02:50.920 --> 02:52.920
the well-known man about town.

02:53.340 --> 02:59.120
It was a nut to crack for many what these two could see in each other, or what subject

02:59.120 --> 03:00.580
they could find in common.

03:01.200 --> 03:06.760
It was reported by those who encountered them in their Sunday walks, that they said nothing,

03:06.760 --> 03:12.500
look singularly dull, and would hail with obvious relief the appearance of a friend.

03:13.480 --> 03:18.840
For all that, the two men put the greatest store by these excursions, counted them the

03:18.840 --> 03:24.700
chief jewel of each week, and not only set aside occasions of pleasure, but even resisted

03:24.700 --> 03:29.040
the cause of business, that they might enjoy them uninterrupted.

03:30.200 --> 03:35.900
It chanced on one of these rambles that their way led them down a by-street in a busy quarter

03:35.900 --> 03:36.500
of London.

03:37.120 --> 03:43.620
The street was small, and what is called quiet, but it drove a thriving trade on the weekdays.

03:44.200 --> 03:49.740
The inhabitants were all doing well, it seemed, and all emulously hoping to do better still,

03:50.120 --> 03:55.300
and laying out the surplus of their grains in coquetry, so that the sharp fronts stood

03:55.300 --> 04:01.040
along that thoroughfare with an air of invitation, like rows of smiling saleswomen.

04:01.580 --> 04:07.660
Even on Sunday, when it veiled its more florid charms, and lay comparatively empty of passage,

04:08.240 --> 04:15.320
the street shone out in contrast to its dingy neighborhood, like a fire in a forest, and

04:15.320 --> 04:21.340
with its freshly painted shutters, well-polished brasses, and general cleanliness and gaiety

04:21.340 --> 04:26.200
of note, instantly caught and pleased the eye of the passenger.

04:27.600 --> 04:34.100
Two doors from one corner, on the left hand going east, the line was broken by the entry

04:34.100 --> 04:40.800
of a court, and just at that point a certain sinister block of building thrust forward

04:40.800 --> 04:42.360
its gable on the street.

04:43.280 --> 04:49.600
It was two stories high, showed no window, nothing but a door on the lower story and

04:49.600 --> 04:55.820
a blind forehead of discolored wall on the upper, and bore in every feature the marks

04:55.820 --> 04:58.720
of prolonged and sordid negligence.

04:59.300 --> 05:05.700
The door, which was equipped with neither bell nor knocker, was blistered and disdained.

05:06.480 --> 05:12.140
Tramps slouched into the recess and struck matches on the panels, children kept shop

05:12.140 --> 05:18.360
under the steps, the schoolboy had tried his knife on the moldings, and for close on a

05:18.360 --> 05:24.960
generation no one had appeared to drive away these random visitors, or to repair their

05:25.980 --> 05:26.700
savages.

05:27.600 --> 05:32.440
Mr. Enfield and the lawyer were on the other side of the by-street, but when they came

05:32.440 --> 05:36.960
abreast of the entry, the former lifted up his cane and pointed.

05:37.800 --> 05:43.740
"'Did you ever remark that door?' he asked, and when his companion had replied in the

05:43.740 --> 05:50.680
affirmative, "'It is connected in my mind,' added he, with a very odd story.'

05:50.680 --> 05:55.080
"'Indeed?' said Mr. Utterson, with a slight change of voice.

05:55.680 --> 05:58.020
"'And what was that?'

05:58.020 --> 06:01.880
"'Well, it was this way,' returned Mr. Enfield.

06:02.460 --> 06:07.540
"'I was coming home from some place at the end of the world about three o'clock of a

06:07.540 --> 06:13.400
black winter morning, and my way lay through a part of town where there was literally nothing

06:13.400 --> 06:19.100
to be seen but lamps, street after street, and all the folks asleep.

06:19.100 --> 06:26.240
Street after street, all lighted up as if for a procession, and all as empty as a church,

06:26.760 --> 06:33.100
till at last I got into that state of mind when a man listens and listens, and begins

06:33.100 --> 06:34.740
to long for the sight of a policeman.

06:35.720 --> 06:49.080
All at once I saw two figures, one a little man who was stumping along eastward at a good

06:49.080 --> 06:50.700
down a cross street.

06:51.660 --> 06:57.940
Well, sir, the two ran into one another naturally enough at the corner, and then came the horrible

06:57.940 --> 07:04.120
part of the thing, for the man trampled calmly over the child's body and left her screaming

07:04.120 --> 07:04.980
on the ground.

07:05.720 --> 07:09.700
It sounds nothing to hear, but it was hellish to see.

07:10.360 --> 07:14.820
It wasn't like a man, it was like some damned juggernaut.

07:15.460 --> 07:22.160
I gave a few, hello, took to my heels, collared my gentleman, and brought him back to where

07:22.160 --> 07:25.180
there was already quite a group about the screaming child.

07:25.960 --> 07:33.460
He was perfectly cool and made no resistance, but gave me one look so ugly that it brought

07:33.460 --> 07:35.880
out the sweat on me like running.

07:36.840 --> 07:42.480
The people who turned out were the girl's own family, and pretty soon the doctor for

07:42.480 --> 07:45.220
whom she had been sent put in his appearance.

07:46.140 --> 07:51.740
Well, the child was not much the worse, more frightened, according to the saw-bones, and

07:51.740 --> 07:57.780
there you might have supposed would be an end to it, but there was one curious circumstance.

07:58.960 --> 08:05.080
I had taken a loathing to my gentleman at first sight, so had the child's family, which

08:05.080 --> 08:09.760
was only natural, but the doctor's case was what struck me.

08:10.060 --> 08:15.700
He was the usual cut-and-dry apothecary of no particular age and colour, with a strong

08:15.700 --> 08:19.940
Edinburgh accent, and about as emotional as a bagpipe.

08:20.780 --> 08:24.340
Well, sir, he was like the rest of us.

08:24.820 --> 08:31.700
Every time he looked at my prisoner I saw that saw-bones turn sick and white with desire

08:31.700 --> 08:32.700
to kill him.

08:33.320 --> 08:39.500
I knew what was in his mind just as he knew what was in mine, and killing being out of

08:39.500 --> 08:42.040
question, we did the next best.

08:42.580 --> 08:48.480
We told the man we could and would make such a scandal out of this as should make his name

08:48.480 --> 08:51.000
stink from one end of London to the other.

08:51.740 --> 08:57.260
If he had any friends or any credit, we undertook that he should lose them.

08:57.960 --> 09:03.260
And all the time, as we were pitching it in red hot, we were keeping the women off him

09:03.260 --> 09:06.960
as best we could, for they were as wild as harpies.

09:06.960 --> 09:13.940
I never saw a circle of such hateful faces, and there was the man in the middle, with

09:13.940 --> 09:16.820
a kind of black, sneering coolness.

09:17.200 --> 09:22.660
Frightened too, I could see that, but carrying it off, sir, really likes Satan.

09:23.540 --> 09:29.740
If you choose to make capital out of this accident, said he, I am naturally helpless.

09:30.580 --> 09:35.040
No gentleman but wishes to avoid a scene, says he.

09:35.800 --> 09:37.040
Name your figure.

09:38.000 --> 09:42.300
Well, we screwed him up to a hundred pounds for the child's family.

09:42.960 --> 09:47.460
He would have clearly liked to stick out, but there was something about the lot of us

09:47.460 --> 09:50.940
that meant mischief, and at last he struck.

09:52.720 --> 09:54.680
The next thing was to get the money.

09:55.200 --> 10:00.240
And where do you think he carried us but to that place with the door?

10:00.240 --> 10:06.860
Whipped out a key, went in, and presently came back with the matter of ten pounds in

10:06.860 --> 10:14.760
gold and a check for the balance on coots, drawn payable to bearer, and signed with a

10:14.760 --> 10:20.640
name that I can't mention, though it's one of the points of my story, but it was a name

10:20.640 --> 10:23.280
at least very well known and often printed.

10:23.820 --> 10:29.640
The figure was stiff, but the signature was good for more than that if it was only genuine.

10:30.280 --> 10:36.200
I took the liberty of pointing out to my gentleman that the whole business looked apocryphal,

10:36.400 --> 10:41.700
and that a man does not, in real life, walk into a cellar door at four in the morning

10:41.700 --> 10:45.840
and come out with another man's check for close upon a hundred pounds.

10:46.640 --> 10:49.920
But he was quite easy and sneering.

10:50.620 --> 10:57.800
Set your mind at rest, says he, I will stay with you till the banks open and cash the

10:57.800 --> 10:58.560
check myself.

10:59.900 --> 11:07.120
So we all set off, the doctor and the child's father and our friend and myself, and passed

11:07.120 --> 11:12.920
the rest of the night in my chambers, and the next day, when we had breakfasted, went

11:12.920 --> 11:14.600
in a body to the bank.

11:15.380 --> 11:20.420
I gave in the check myself, and said I had every reason to believe it was a forgery.

11:21.360 --> 11:24.520
Not a bit of it, the check was genuine.

11:25.080 --> 11:27.900
Tot-tot! said Utterson.

11:28.280 --> 11:31.600
I see you feel as I do, said Mr. Enfield.

11:32.220 --> 11:39.860
Yes, it's a bad story, for my man was a fellow that nobody could have to do with, a really

11:39.860 --> 11:45.540
damnable man, and the person that drew the check is the very pink of the proprieties.

11:46.140 --> 11:52.520
Celebrated too, and, what makes it worse, one of your fellows who do what they call

11:52.520 --> 11:53.180
good.

11:54.080 --> 11:59.860
Blackmail, I suppose, an honest man paying through the nose for some of the capers of

11:59.860 --> 12:00.460
his youth.

12:01.080 --> 12:07.280
Blackmail House is what I call the place with the door in consequence, though even that,

12:07.280 --> 12:14.780
you know, is far from explaining all, he added, and with the words fell into a vein of musing.

12:15.780 --> 12:23.040
From this he was recalled by Mr. Utterson asking rather suddenly, and you don't know

12:23.040 --> 12:25.340
if the drawer of the check lives there.

12:26.040 --> 12:32.920
A likely place isn't it, returned Mr. Enfield, but I happen to have noticed his address,

12:33.280 --> 12:35.720
he lives in some square or other.

12:36.320 --> 12:40.660
And you never asked about the place with the door, said Mr. Utterson.

12:41.600 --> 12:45.660
No, sir, I had a delicacy, was the reply.

12:46.260 --> 12:52.920
I feel very strongly about putting questions, it partakes too much of the style of the day

12:52.920 --> 12:53.600
of judgment.

12:53.960 --> 12:57.800
You start a question, and it's like starting a stone.

12:58.540 --> 13:04.900
You sit quietly on the top of a hill, and away the stone goes, starting others, and

13:04.900 --> 13:10.760
presently some bland old bird, the last you would have thought of, is knocked on the head

13:10.760 --> 13:15.040
in his own back garden, and the family have to change their name.

13:15.740 --> 13:18.640
No, sir, I make it a rule of mine.

13:18.640 --> 13:22.720
The more it looks like queer streets, the less I ask.

13:23.840 --> 13:26.800
A very good rule too, said the lawyer.

13:27.700 --> 13:32.500
But I have studied the place for myself, continued Mr. Enfield.

13:32.980 --> 13:35.340
It seems scarcely a house.

13:35.760 --> 13:42.280
There is no other door, and nobody goes in or out of that one, but once in a great while

13:42.280 --> 13:43.860
the gentleman of my adventure.

13:43.860 --> 13:49.500
There are three windows looking on the court on the first floor, none below.

13:50.040 --> 13:53.280
The windows are always shut, but they're clean.

13:53.680 --> 13:59.280
And then there is a chimney which is generally smoking, so somebody must live there.

13:59.920 --> 14:06.060
And yet it's not so sure, for the buildings are so packed together about the court that

14:06.060 --> 14:09.340
it's hard to say where one ends and another begins.

14:10.140 --> 14:15.600
The pair walked on again for a while in silence, and then—

14:15.600 --> 14:20.860
Enfield, said Mr. Utterson, that's a good rule of yours.

14:21.680 --> 14:24.940
Yes, I think it is, returned Enfield.

14:26.140 --> 14:32.280
But for all that, continued the lawyer, there is one point I want to ask.

14:32.880 --> 14:36.840
I want to ask the name of that man who walked over the child.

14:37.620 --> 14:43.120
Well, said Mr. Enfield, I can't see what harm it would do.

14:43.660 --> 14:46.420
It was a man of the name of Hyde.

14:47.560 --> 14:52.460
Hmm, said Utterson, what sort of a man is he to see?

14:53.420 --> 14:55.820
He is not easy to describe.

14:56.520 --> 15:02.560
There is something wrong with his appearance, something displeasing, something downright

15:02.560 --> 15:03.460
detestable.

15:03.980 --> 15:09.200
I never saw a man I so disliked, and yet I scarce know why.

15:09.920 --> 15:16.140
He must be deformed somewhere, he gives a strong feeling of deformity, although I can't

15:16.140 --> 15:17.420
specify the point.

15:17.900 --> 15:23.380
He's an extraordinary-looking man, and yet I really can name nothing out of the way.

15:24.140 --> 15:27.680
No, sir, I can make no hand of it.

15:27.680 --> 15:34.880
I can't describe him, and it's not want of memory, for I declare I can see him this moment.

15:35.960 --> 15:42.420
Mr. Utterson again walked some way in silence, and obviously under a weight of consideration.

15:43.400 --> 15:45.520
You are sure he used a key?

15:46.120 --> 15:47.500
He inquired at last.

15:48.000 --> 15:52.900
My dear sir, began Enfield, surprised out of himself.

15:53.620 --> 15:59.040
Yes, I know, said Utterson, I know it must seem strange.

15:59.960 --> 16:05.980
The fact is, if I do not ask you the name of the other party, it's because I know it

16:05.980 --> 16:06.540
already.

16:07.220 --> 16:10.580
You see, Richard, your tale has gone home.

16:11.140 --> 16:15.600
If you have been inexact in any point, you had better correct it.

16:16.300 --> 16:21.900
I think you might have warned me, returned the other with a touch of solidness.

16:22.400 --> 16:26.400
But I have been pedantically exact, as you call it.

16:26.740 --> 16:30.700
The fellow had a key, and what's more, he has it still.

16:31.320 --> 16:33.780
I saw him use it not a week ago.

16:34.440 --> 16:41.820
Mr. Utterson sighed deeply, but said never a word, and the young man presently resumed.

16:42.340 --> 16:46.500
Here is another lesson to say nothing, said he.

16:46.940 --> 16:49.480
I am ashamed of my long tongue.

16:50.160 --> 16:53.980
Let us make a bargain never to refer to this again.

16:55.160 --> 16:57.860
With all my heart, said the lawyer.

16:58.180 --> 17:00.820
I shake hands on that, Richard.

17:04.160 --> 17:06.760
Search for Mr. Hyde

17:07.620 --> 17:13.600
That evening Mr. Utterson came home to his bachelor house in sombre spirits, and sat

17:13.600 --> 17:15.460
down to dinner without relish.

17:16.140 --> 17:23.400
It was his custom of a Sunday, when this meal was over, to sit close by the fire, a volume

17:23.400 --> 17:28.900
of some dry divinity on his reading-desk, until the clock of the neighbouring church

17:28.900 --> 17:34.420
rang out the hour of twelve, when he would go soberly and gratefully to bed.

17:35.240 --> 17:41.080
On this night, however, as soon as the cloth was taken away, he took up a candle and went

17:41.080 --> 17:42.420
into his business-room.

17:43.200 --> 17:49.200
There he opened his safe, took from the most private part of it a document endorsed on

17:49.200 --> 17:56.280
the envelope as Dr. Jekyll's Will, and sat down with a clouded brow to study its contents.

17:57.360 --> 18:03.380
The Will was holograph, for Mr. Utterson, though he took charge of it now it was made,

18:03.780 --> 18:07.260
had refused to lend the least assistance in the making of it.

18:07.810 --> 18:17.460
It provided not only that in case of the decease of Henry Jekyll, MD, DCL, LLD, FRS, etc.,

18:17.460 --> 18:22.720
all his possessions were to pass into the hands of his friend and benefactor Edward

18:22.720 --> 18:29.740
Hyde, but that in case of Dr. Jekyll's disappearance or unexplained absence for any period exceeding

18:29.740 --> 18:36.220
three calendar months, the sad Edward Hyde should step into the said Henry Jekyll's shoes

18:36.220 --> 18:42.060
without further delay, and free from any burden or obligation beyond the payment of

18:42.060 --> 18:45.160
a few small sums to the members of the doctor's household.

18:46.580 --> 18:50.400
This document had long been the lawyer's eyesore.

18:50.740 --> 18:56.980
It offended him both as a lawyer and as a lover of the sane and customary sides of life,

18:57.580 --> 19:04.160
to whom the fanciful was the immodest, and hitherto it was his ignorance of Mr. Hyde

19:04.160 --> 19:05.900
that had swelled his indignation.

19:06.480 --> 19:09.880
Now by a sudden turn it was his knowledge.

19:10.840 --> 19:15.880
It was already bad enough when the name was but a name of which he could learn no more.

19:16.320 --> 19:22.440
It was worse when it began to be closed upon with detestable attributes, and out of the

19:22.440 --> 19:28.860
shifting insubstantial mists that had so long baffled his eye, there leaped up the sudden

19:28.860 --> 19:31.460
definite presentment of a fiend.

19:32.240 --> 19:40.300
I thought it was madness, he said, as he replaced the obnoxious paper in the safe, and now I

19:40.300 --> 19:42.400
begin to fear it is disgrace.

19:43.500 --> 19:48.920
With that he blew out his candle, put on a greatcoat, and set forth in the direction

19:48.920 --> 19:55.580
of Cavendish Square, the citadel of medicine, where his friend the great Dr. Lanyon had

19:55.580 --> 19:58.300
his house and received his crowding patients.

19:59.020 --> 20:02.720
If anyone knows, it will be Lanyon, he had thought.

20:04.160 --> 20:06.860
The solemn butler knew and welcomed him.

20:07.140 --> 20:12.420
He was subjected to no stage of delay, but ushered direct from the door to the dining

20:12.420 --> 20:16.000
room, where Dr. Lanyon sat alone over his wine.

20:16.780 --> 20:23.020
This was a hearty, healthy, dapper red-faced gentleman, with a shock of hair prematurely

20:23.020 --> 20:25.860
white, and a boisterous and decided manner.

20:26.580 --> 20:32.820
At sight of Mr. Utterson, he sprang up from his chair and welcomed him with both hands.

20:33.260 --> 20:39.780
The geniality, as was the way of the man, was somewhat theatrical to the eye, but it

20:39.780 --> 20:41.760
deposed on genuine feeling.

20:42.340 --> 20:48.560
For these two were old friends, old mates both at school and college, both thorough

20:48.560 --> 20:55.220
respectors of themselves and of each other, and what does not always follow, men who thoroughly

20:55.220 --> 20:57.060
enjoyed each other's company.

20:58.140 --> 21:04.120
After a little rambling talk, the lawyer led up to the subject which so disagreeably

21:04.120 --> 21:05.700
preoccupied his mind.

21:07.220 --> 21:14.500
Um, I suppose, Lanyon, said he, you and I must be the two oldest friends that Henry

21:14.500 --> 21:15.600
Jekyll has.

21:16.260 --> 21:23.340
I wish the friends were younger, chuckled Dr. Lanyon, but I suppose we are, and what

21:23.340 --> 21:23.880
of that?

21:24.140 --> 21:25.920
I see little of him now.

21:26.940 --> 21:31.360
Indeed, said Utterson, I thought you had a bond of common interest.

21:31.860 --> 21:38.100
We had, was the reply, but it is more than ten years since Henry Jekyll became too

21:38.100 --> 21:39.320
fanciful for me.

21:39.620 --> 21:46.040
He began to go wrong, wrong in mind, and, and though, of course, I continue to take

21:46.040 --> 21:52.220
an interest in him from old sakes' sake, as they say, I see, and I have seen,

21:52.220 --> 21:54.080
devilishly little of the man.

21:54.640 --> 22:01.380
Such unscientific balderdash, added the doctor, flushing suddenly purple, would have

22:01.380 --> 22:03.660
estranged Damon and Pytheas.

22:04.340 --> 22:09.400
This little spirit of temper was somewhat of a relief to Mr. Utterson.

22:10.100 --> 22:15.660
They have only differed on some point of science, he thought, and being a man of no

22:16.220 --> 22:23.280
passions, except in the matter of conveyancing, he even added, it is nothing worse than that.

22:24.340 --> 22:29.560
He gave his friend a few seconds to recover his composure, and then approached the question

22:29.560 --> 22:30.840
he had come to put.

22:31.500 --> 22:37.480
Did you ever come across a protege of his, one Hyde?

22:38.020 --> 22:38.840
He asked.

22:39.720 --> 22:40.080
Hyde?

22:40.700 --> 22:41.580
Repeated Lanyon.

22:42.460 --> 22:44.720
No, never heard of him.

22:44.720 --> 22:45.980
Since my time.

22:46.800 --> 22:51.380
That was the amount of information that the lawyer carried back with him to the great

22:51.380 --> 22:57.840
dark bed on which he tossed to and fro, until the small hours of the morning began to grow large.

22:58.520 --> 23:04.280
It was a night of little ease to his toiling mind, toiling in mere darkness and besieged by

23:04.280 --> 23:04.880
questions.

23:05.920 --> 23:14.700
Six o'clock struck on the bells of the church that was so conveniently near to Mr. Utterson's

23:14.700 --> 23:15.260
problem.

23:16.080 --> 23:22.940
Hitherto it had touched him on the intellectual side alone, but now his imagination also was

23:22.940 --> 23:29.380
engaged, or rather enslaved, and as he lay and tossed in the gross darkness of the night

23:29.380 --> 23:36.140
and the curtained room, Mr. Enfield's tale went by before his mind in a scroll of lighted

23:36.140 --> 23:36.620
pictures.

23:37.380 --> 23:44.160
He would be aware of the great field of lamps of a nocturnal city, then of the figure of a man

23:44.160 --> 23:52.200
walking swiftly, and then of a child running from the doctors, and then these met, and that human

23:52.200 --> 23:58.060
juggernaut trod the child down and passed on, regardless of her screams.

23:58.820 --> 24:05.100
Or else he would see a room in a rich house, where his friend lay asleep, dreaming and

24:05.100 --> 24:11.460
smiling at his dreams, and then the door of that room would be opened, the curtains of the bed

24:11.460 --> 24:20.160
plucked apart, the sleeper recalled, and lo, there would stand by his side a figure to whom power was

24:20.160 --> 24:25.460
given, and even at that dead hour he must rise and do its bidding.

24:26.880 --> 24:33.720
The figure in these two phases haunted the lawyer all night, and if at any time he dozed over,

24:34.140 --> 24:40.200
it was but to see it glide more stealthily through sleeping houses, or move the more swiftly,

24:40.200 --> 24:46.820
and still the more swiftly, even to dizziness, through wider labyrinths of lamp-lighted city,

24:47.440 --> 24:51.960
and at every street corner crush a child and leave for screaming.

24:52.980 --> 24:57.140
And still the figure had no face by which he might know it.

24:57.860 --> 25:03.560
Even in his dreams it had no face, or one that baffled him and melted before his eyes,

25:04.000 --> 25:09.060
and thus it was that there sprang up, and grew a pace in the lawyer's mind,

25:09.060 --> 25:16.400
a singularly strong, almost an inordinate, curiosity to behold the features of the real

25:16.400 --> 25:22.960
Mr. Hyde. If he could but once set eyes on him, he thought the mystery would lighten,

25:23.020 --> 25:28.900
and perhaps roll altogether away, as was the habit of mysterious things when well examined.

25:29.500 --> 25:36.120
He might see a reason for his friend's strange preference, or bondage, call it which you please,

25:36.120 --> 25:42.640
and even for the startling claws of the will. At least it would be a face worth seeing,

25:43.140 --> 25:50.020
the face of a man who was without bowels of mercy, a face which had but to show itself

25:50.020 --> 25:56.400
to raise up in the mind of the unimpressionable Enfield a spirit of enduring hatred.

25:57.160 --> 26:02.360
From that time forward Mr. Utterson began to haunt the door in the by-street of shops.

26:02.360 --> 26:08.220
In the morning before office hours, at noon when business was plenty and time scarce,

26:08.700 --> 26:16.220
at night under the face of the fogged city moon, by all lights and all hours of solitude or concourse

26:16.220 --> 26:19.940
the lawyer was to be found on his chosen post.

26:21.560 --> 26:27.400
If he be Mr. Hyde, he had thought, I shall be Mr. Seek.

26:28.620 --> 26:36.620
And at last his patience was rewarded. It was a fine, dry night. Frost in the air,

26:36.820 --> 26:42.200
the streets as clean as a ballroom floor, the lamps unshaken by any wind,

26:42.680 --> 26:49.140
drawing a regular pattern of light and shadow. By ten o'clock, when the shops were closed,

26:49.560 --> 26:55.100
the by-street was very solitary, and in spite of the low growl of London from all round,

26:55.100 --> 27:02.460
very silent. Small sounds carried far. Domestic sounds out of the houses were clearly audible

27:02.460 --> 27:08.140
on either side of the roadway, and the rumour of the approach of any passenger preceded him

27:08.140 --> 27:15.620
by a long time. Mr. Utterson had been some minutes at his post when he was aware of an odd

27:15.620 --> 27:22.660
light footstep drawing near. In the course of his nightly patrols he had long grown accustomed to

27:22.660 --> 27:28.280
quaint effect with which the footfalls of a single person, while he still is a great way off,

27:28.600 --> 27:35.020
suddenly sprang out distinct from the vast hum and clatter of the city. Yet his attention had

27:35.020 --> 27:41.940
never before been so sharply and decisively arrested, and it was with a strong superstitious

27:41.940 --> 27:49.440
prevision of success that he withdrew into the entry of the court. The steps drew swiftly

27:49.440 --> 27:54.160
nearer, and swelled out suddenly louder as they turned the end of the street.

27:54.900 --> 28:01.680
The lawyer, looking forth from the entry, could soon see what manner of man he had to deal with.

28:02.240 --> 28:07.560
He was small and very plainly dressed, and the look of him, even at that distance,

28:07.940 --> 28:14.180
went somehow strongly against the watch's inclination. But he made straight for the

28:14.180 --> 28:20.860
crossing the roadway to save time, and as he came he drew a key from his pocket like

28:20.860 --> 28:27.700
one approaching home. Mr. Utterson stepped out and touched him on the shoulder as he passed.

28:28.240 --> 28:34.320
Mr. Hyde, I think. Mr. Hyde shrank back with a hissing intake of the breath,

28:34.920 --> 28:40.100
but his fear was only momentary, and though he did not look the lawyer in the face,

28:40.100 --> 28:42.300
he answered coolly enough.

28:43.160 --> 28:46.000
That is my name. What do you want?

28:47.340 --> 28:53.760
I see you are going in, returned the lawyer. I am an old friend of Dr. Jekyll's,

28:53.940 --> 28:57.740
Mr. Utterson of Gaunt Street. You must have heard of my name,

28:58.240 --> 29:02.240
and meeting you so conveniently, I thought you might admit me.

29:03.060 --> 29:09.960
You will not find Dr. Jekyll. He is from home, replied Mr. Hyde, blowing in the key.

29:10.100 --> 29:13.680
And then suddenly, but still without looking up,

29:13.900 --> 29:16.660
How do you know me? he asked.

29:18.020 --> 29:22.200
On your side, said Mr. Utterson, will you do me a favour?

29:22.840 --> 29:26.880
With pleasure, replied the other. What shall it be?

29:27.920 --> 29:32.260
Will you let me see your face? asked the lawyer.

29:33.340 --> 29:38.880
Mr. Hyde appeared to hesitate, and then, as if upon some sudden reflection,

29:38.880 --> 29:45.620
fronted about with an air of defiance, and the pair stared at each other pretty fixedly

29:45.620 --> 29:53.000
for a few seconds. Now I shall know you again, said Mr. Utterson. It may be useful.

29:54.500 --> 30:01.740
Yes, returned Mr. Hyde. It is as well we have met, and apropos,

30:01.860 --> 30:07.500
you should have my address, and he gave a number of a street in Soho.

30:08.380 --> 30:14.040
Good God! thought Mr. Utterson. Can he too have been thinking of the will?

30:15.160 --> 30:20.780
But he kept his feelings to himself, and only granted an acknowledgement of the address.

30:21.900 --> 30:26.320
And now, said the other, how did you know me?

30:27.240 --> 30:31.360
By description, was the reply. Whose description?

30:32.220 --> 30:35.840
We have common friends, said Mr. Utterson.

30:36.560 --> 30:42.740
Common friends, echoed Mr. Hyde a little hoarsely. Who are they?

30:43.700 --> 30:46.740
Jackal, for instance, said the lawyer.

30:47.300 --> 30:52.420
He never told you, cried Mr. Hyde, and with a flush of anger,

30:52.900 --> 30:55.920
I did not think you would have lied.

30:56.700 --> 31:00.860
Come, said Mr. Utterson, that is not fitting language.

31:01.740 --> 31:07.020
The other snarled aloud into a savage laugh, and in the next moment,

31:07.380 --> 31:12.860
with extraordinary quickness, he had unlocked the door and disappeared into the house.

31:14.040 --> 31:19.280
The lawyer stood awhile when Mr. Hyde had left him, the picture of disquietude.

31:20.220 --> 31:22.640
Then he began slowly to mount the street,

31:23.220 --> 31:28.540
passing every step or two, and putting his head to his brow like a man in mental perplexity.

31:29.280 --> 31:36.060
The problem he was thus debating as he walked was one of a class that is rarely solved.

31:37.020 --> 31:43.000
Mr. Hyde was pale and dwarfish. He gave an impression of deformity without any

31:43.000 --> 31:49.960
nameable malformation. He had a displeasing smile, he had borne himself to the lawyer with a sort of

31:49.960 --> 31:56.620
murderous mixture of timidity and boldness, and he spoke with a husky, whispering, and somewhat

31:56.620 --> 32:04.440
broken voice. All of these were points against him, but not all of these together could explain

32:04.440 --> 32:11.540
the hitherto unknown disgust, loathing, and fear with which Mr. Utterson regarded him.

32:12.480 --> 32:16.360
There must be something else, said the perplexed gentleman.

32:16.920 --> 32:20.560
There is something more, if I could find a name for it.

32:20.560 --> 32:28.260
God bless me, the man seems hardly human. Something troglodytic, shall we say.

32:28.640 --> 32:36.280
Or can it be the old story of Dr. Fell? Or is it the mere radiance of a foul soul that

32:36.280 --> 32:45.680
thus transpires through and transfigures its clay continent? The last, I think. For, oh my

32:45.680 --> 32:53.480
poor old Harry Jekyll, if ever I read Satan's signature upon a face, it is on that of your new

32:53.480 --> 33:01.240
friend. Round the corner from the By Street there was a square of ancient, handsome houses,

33:01.780 --> 33:08.480
now for the most part decayed from their high estate, and let in flats and chambers to all

33:08.480 --> 33:15.220
sorts and conditions of men, map engravers, architects, shady lawyers, and the agents of

33:15.220 --> 33:22.880
secure enterprises. One house, however, second from the corner, was still occupied entire,

33:23.240 --> 33:29.260
and at the door of this, which wore a great air of wealth and comfort, though it was now plunged

33:29.260 --> 33:36.760
in darkness except for the fan-light, Mr. Utterson stopped and knocked. A well-dressed elderly

33:36.760 --> 33:44.440
servant opened the door. Is Dr. Jekyll at home, Poole? asked the lawyer. I will see,

33:44.440 --> 33:51.540
Mr. Utterson, said Poole, admitting the visitor as he spoke, into a large low-roofed comfortable

33:51.540 --> 33:58.020
hall, paved with flags, warmed, after the fashion of a country house, by a bright open fire,

33:58.620 --> 34:04.940
and furnished with costly cabinets of oak. Will you wait here by the fire, sir,

34:05.100 --> 34:11.800
or shall I give you a light in the dining-room? Here, thank you, said the lawyer, and he drew

34:11.800 --> 34:19.880
near and leaned on the tall fender. This hall, in which he was now left alone, was a pet fancy of

34:19.880 --> 34:26.100
his friend the doctors, and Utterson himself was wont to speak of it as the pleasantest room in

34:26.100 --> 34:33.280
London. But to-night there was a shudder in his blood, and the face of Hyde sat heavy on his

34:34.010 --> 34:42.560
He felt, what was rare with him, a nausea and distaste of life, and in the gloom of his spirit

34:42.560 --> 34:48.280
he seemed to read a menace in the flickering of the fire-lights on the polished cabinets

34:48.280 --> 34:56.940
and the uneasy starting of the shadow on the roof. He was ashamed of his relief when Poole presently

34:56.940 --> 35:00.040
returned to announce that Dr. Jekyll was gone out.

35:00.480 --> 35:08.180
I saw Mr. Hyde go in by the old dissecting-room, Poole, he said. Is that right, when Dr. Jekyll

35:08.180 --> 35:15.920
is from home? Quite right, Mr. Utterson, sir, replied the servant. Mr. Hyde has a key.

35:16.720 --> 35:21.500
Your master seems to repose a great deal of trust in that young man, Poole,

35:21.500 --> 35:23.620
resumed the other amusingly.

35:24.280 --> 35:30.120
Yes, sir, he does indeed, said Poole. We all have orders to obey him.

35:30.860 --> 35:35.560
I do not think I ever met Mr. Hyde, asked Utterson.

35:36.180 --> 35:44.720
Oh dear no, sir, he never dines here, replied the butler. Indeed we see very little of him on this

35:44.720 --> 35:48.680
side of the house. He mostly comes and goes by the laboratory.

35:49.720 --> 35:51.820
Well, good night, Poole.

35:52.420 --> 35:54.420
Good night, Mr. Utterson.

35:55.640 --> 35:59.520
And the lawyer set out homeward with a very heavy heart.

36:00.700 --> 36:07.340
Poor Harry Jekyll, he thought. My mind misgives me he is in deep waters.

36:08.080 --> 36:12.840
He was wild when he was young, a long while ago to be sure,

36:12.840 --> 36:16.600
but in the law of God there is no statute of limitations.

36:17.840 --> 36:25.060
Ay, it must be that. The ghost of some old sin, the cancer of some concealed disgrace,

36:25.640 --> 36:33.060
punishment coming, payday cloud-o, years after memory has forgotten and self-love condoned the

36:33.060 --> 36:41.300
fault. And the lawyer, scared by the thought, brooded a while on his own past, groping in all

36:41.300 --> 36:47.840
corners of memory, lest by chance some jack in the box of an old iniquity should leap to light

36:47.840 --> 36:54.740
there. His past was fairly blameless. Few men could read the roles of their life with less

36:54.740 --> 37:01.100
apprehension. Yet he was humbled to the dust by the many ill things he had done,

37:01.700 --> 37:07.980
and raised up again into sober and fearful gratitude by the many he had come so near to doing,

37:07.980 --> 37:15.780
yet avoided. And then, by a return on his former subject, he conceived a spark of hope.

37:16.440 --> 37:24.360
This master-hide, if he were studied, thought he, must have secrets of his own, black secrets by

37:24.360 --> 37:30.040
the look of him, secrets compared to which poor Jekyll's worst would be like sunshine.

37:30.040 --> 37:39.480
But things cannot continue as they are. It turns me cold to think of this creature stealing like a

37:39.480 --> 37:48.180
thief to Harry's bedside. Poor Harry, what awakening! And the danger of it, for if this hide

37:48.180 --> 37:57.680
suspects the existence of the will, he may grow impatient to inherit. I must put my shoulders to

37:57.680 --> 38:05.760
wheel. If Jekyll will but let me, he added, if Jekyll will only let me. For once more,

38:05.980 --> 38:13.640
he saw before his mind's eye, as clear as transparency, the strange clauses of the will.

38:16.940 --> 38:19.760
Doctor Jekyll was quite at ease.

38:20.900 --> 38:27.600
A fortnight later, by excellent good fortune, the doctor gave one of his pleasant dinners

38:27.600 --> 38:34.980
to some five or six old cronies, all intelligent reputable men, and all judges of good wine.

38:35.720 --> 38:40.900
And Mr. Utterson so contrived that he remained behind after the others had departed.

38:41.680 --> 38:47.040
This was no new arrangement, but a thing that had befallen many scores of times.

38:47.760 --> 38:54.680
Where Utterson was liked, he was liked well. Hosts loved to detain the dry lawyer when the

38:54.680 --> 39:00.400
light-hearted and loose-tongued had already their foot on the threshold. They liked to sit a while

39:00.400 --> 39:06.600
in his unobtrusive company, practicing for solitude, sobering their minds in the man's

39:06.600 --> 39:13.920
rich silence after the expense and strain of gaiety. To this rule Dr. Jekyll was no exception,

39:13.920 --> 39:21.440
and as he now sat on the opposite side of the fire, a large well-made smooth-faced man of fifty,

39:22.060 --> 39:27.320
with something of a stylish caste perhaps, but every mark of capacity and kindness,

39:28.140 --> 39:34.780
you could see by his looks that he cherished for Mr. Utterson a sincere and warm affection.

39:35.600 --> 39:41.200
I have been wanting to speak to you, Jekyll," began the latter.

39:41.380 --> 39:43.740
You know that will of yours?

39:44.880 --> 39:49.780
A close observer might have gathered that the topic was distasteful,

39:50.120 --> 39:52.820
but the doctor carried it off gaily.

39:53.520 --> 39:59.600
My poor Utterson, said he, you are unfortunate in such a client.

39:59.600 --> 40:06.780
I never saw a man so distressed as you were by my will, unless it were that hide-bound

40:06.780 --> 40:14.460
pedant Lanyon, at what he called my scientific heresies. Oh, I know he's a good fellow,

40:14.580 --> 40:20.120
you needn't frown, an excellent fellow, and I always mean to see more of him.

40:20.520 --> 40:27.500
But a hide-bound pedant for all that, an ignorant, blatant pedant, I was never more

40:27.500 --> 40:29.940
disappointed in any man than Lanyon.

40:31.000 --> 40:37.580
You know I never approved of it, pursued Utterson, ruthlessly disregarding the fresh topic.

40:38.240 --> 40:39.120
My will?

40:40.180 --> 40:47.460
Yes, certainly I know that, said the doctor, a trifle sharply. You have told me so.

40:48.480 --> 40:54.800
Well, I tell you so again, continued the lawyer. I have been learning something of young hide.

40:55.380 --> 41:02.700
The large handsome face of Dr. Juckle grew pale to the very lips, and there came a blackness

41:02.700 --> 41:11.860
about his eyes. I do not care to hear more, said he. This is a matter I thought we had agreed to

41:11.860 --> 41:22.080
drop. What I heard was abominable, said Utterson. It can make no change. You do not understand my

41:22.080 --> 41:29.400
position, returned the doctor with a certain incoherency of manner. I am painfully situated,

41:29.620 --> 41:38.240
Utterson. My position is a very strange—a very strange one. It is one of those affairs that cannot

41:38.240 --> 41:51.420
be mended by talking. Juckle, said Utterson, you know me. I am a man to be trusted. Make a clean

41:51.420 --> 41:53.040
I can get you out of it.

41:53.820 --> 42:02.660
My good Utterson, said the doctor, this is very good of you, this is downright good of you,

42:03.020 --> 42:10.760
and I cannot find words to thank you in. I believe you fully. I would trust you before

42:10.760 --> 42:19.840
any man alive, I before myself, if I could make the choice. But indeed it isn't what you fancy.

42:19.840 --> 42:27.880
It's not as bad as that, and just to put your good heart at rest, I will tell you one thing.

42:28.620 --> 42:36.620
The moment I choose, I can be rid of Mr. Hyde. I give you my hand upon it,

42:36.980 --> 42:43.760
and I thank you again and again. And I will just add one little word, Utterson,

42:43.760 --> 42:53.160
that I'm sure you'll take in good part. This is a private matter, and I beg of you to let it sleep.

42:54.160 --> 42:57.440
Utterson reflected a little, looking in the fire.

42:58.780 --> 43:04.780
I have no doubt you are perfectly right, he said at last, getting to his feet.

43:05.660 --> 43:12.140
Well, but since you have touched upon this business, and for the last time, I hope,

43:12.140 --> 43:17.900
continued the doctor, there is one point I should like you to understand.

43:18.560 --> 43:26.320
I have really a very great interest in poor Hyde. I know you have seen him, he told me so,

43:26.460 --> 43:35.620
and I fear he was rude. But I do sincerely take a great, a very great interest in that young man.

43:35.620 --> 43:42.560
And if I am taken away, Utterson, I wish you to promise me that you will bear with him

43:42.560 --> 43:50.640
and get his rights for him. I think you would, if you knew all, and it would be a weight off my mind

43:50.640 --> 43:57.140
if you would promise. I can't pretend that I shall ever like him, said the lawyer.

43:57.140 --> 44:05.800
I don't ask that, pleaded Jackal, laying his hand upon the other's arm. I only ask for justice.

44:06.160 --> 44:12.580
I only ask you to help him, for my sake, when I am no longer here.

44:13.720 --> 44:16.740
Utterson heaved an irrepressible sigh.

44:17.660 --> 44:22.100
Well, said he, I promise.

44:24.320 --> 44:26.980
End of part one.

